<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Day One — LIMS BA Field Training</title>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Oswald:wght@400;500;600;700&family=Inter:wght@400;500;600&family=IBM+Plex+Mono:wght@400;500;600&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<style>
  :root{
    --bg: #10171a;
    --panel: #182226;
    --panel-2: #1e2a2f;
    --line: #2b393f;
    --amber: #e8a33d;
    --teal: #4fa9a3;
    --danger: #d9534f;
    --text: #eceff0;
    --text-dim: #8fa0a3;
    --mono: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    --display: 'Oswald', sans-serif;
    --body: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  }
  *{box-sizing:border-box;}
  body{
    margin:0; background:var(--bg); color:var(--text);
    font-family:var(--body); -webkit-font-smoothing:antialiased;
  }
  .app{ display:flex; min-height:100vh; }

  .rail{
    width:280px; flex-shrink:0; background:var(--panel);
    border-right:1px solid var(--line); padding:20px 0 20px 0;
    display:flex; flex-direction:column;
  }
  .rail-head{ padding:0 20px 18px 20px; border-bottom:1px solid var(--line); margin-bottom:8px;}
  .rail-head .kicker{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10.5px; letter-spacing:.14em; color:var(--amber); text-transform:uppercase;}
  .rail-head h1{ font-family:var(--display); font-size:19px; font-weight:600; margin:6px 0 4px; line-height:1.15;}
  .rail-head p{ font-size:11.5px; color:var(--text-dim); margin:0; line-height:1.5;}

  .rail-scroll{ overflow-y:auto; flex:1; }
  .cat-head{
    font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10px; letter-spacing:.12em; text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--text-dim); padding:16px 20px 6px; border-top:1px solid var(--line); margin-top:6px;
  }
  .cat-head:first-child{ border-top:none; margin-top:0; }

  .stage-btn{
    display:flex; align-items:center; gap:10px; width:100%; text-align:left;
    background:none; border:none; color:var(--text); cursor:pointer;
    padding:9px 20px; font-family:var(--body); font-size:12.5px; position:relative;
    border-left:3px solid transparent;
  }
  .stage-btn:hover{ background:var(--panel-2); }
  .stage-btn.active{ background:var(--panel-2); border-left:3px solid var(--amber); }
  .stage-num{
    font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10.5px; color:var(--text-dim); width:20px; flex-shrink:0;
  }
  .stage-btn.active .stage-num{ color:var(--amber); }
  .stage-label{ flex:1; line-height:1.3; }
  .stage-check{
    font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10px; color:var(--teal); flex-shrink:0; opacity:0;
  }
  .stage-check.done{ opacity:1; }

  .rail-foot{ padding:16px 20px 0; border-top:1px solid var(--line);}
  .progress-track{ height:5px; background:var(--line); border-radius:3px; overflow:hidden; margin-bottom:6px;}
  .progress-fill{ height:100%; background:var(--amber); width:0%; transition:width .3s;}
  .progress-text{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10.5px; color:var(--text-dim);}
  .reset-btn{
    margin-top:12px; background:none; border:1px solid var(--line); color:var(--text-dim);
    font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10px; padding:6px 10px; border-radius:4px; cursor:pointer; width:100%;
  }
  .reset-btn:hover{ border-color:var(--danger); color:var(--danger); }

  .main{ flex:1; padding:36px 48px 80px; max-width:840px; }
  .label-card{
    display:inline-flex; align-items:center; gap:10px;
    font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10.5px; letter-spacing:.1em; text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--amber); border:1px solid var(--line); padding:5px 10px 5px 0; border-radius:2px; margin-bottom:14px;
  }
  .label-card .tab-notch{ background:var(--amber); color:#10171a; padding:5px 8px; font-weight:600; }
  .cat-pill{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10px; color:var(--teal); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.1em; margin-bottom:8px; }
  .stage-title{ font-family:var(--display); font-size:29px; font-weight:600; margin:0 0 6px; line-height:1.2;}
  .stage-sub{ color:var(--text-dim); font-size:13.5px; margin:0 0 26px; }

  .mentor{
    background:var(--panel); border:1px solid var(--line); border-left:3px solid var(--teal);
    border-radius:4px; padding:20px 22px; margin-bottom:22px;
  }
  .mentor .who{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10.5px; color:var(--teal); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.1em; margin-bottom:10px; }
  .mentor p{ margin:0 0 12px; font-size:14px; line-height:1.7; color:var(--text); }
  .mentor p:last-child{ margin-bottom:0; }
  .mentor .term{ font-family:var(--mono); color:var(--amber); font-size:12.5px; }

  .panel-card{
    background:var(--panel-2); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:4px; padding:20px 22px; margin-bottom:20px;
  }
  .panel-card h3{ font-family:var(--display); font-size:16px; font-weight:500; margin:0 0 12px; letter-spacing:.02em; }
  .panel-card .note-block{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:12px; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--bg); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:3px; padding:12px 14px; line-height:1.6; white-space:pre-wrap; margin-bottom:14px;}

  textarea{
    width:100%; min-height:120px; background:var(--bg); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:4px;
    color:var(--text); font-family:var(--body); font-size:13.5px; line-height:1.6; padding:14px; resize:vertical;
  }
  textarea:focus{ outline:none; border-color:var(--amber); }

  .btn-row{ display:flex; gap:10px; margin-top:14px; flex-wrap:wrap; }
  button.act{
    font-family:var(--mono); font-size:11.5px; letter-spacing:.05em; text-transform:uppercase;
    padding:9px 16px; border-radius:3px; cursor:pointer; border:1px solid var(--line); background:transparent; color:var(--text);
  }
  button.act:hover{ border-color:var(--amber); color:var(--amber); }
  button.act.primary{ background:var(--amber); color:#10171a; border-color:var(--amber); font-weight:600;}
  button.act.primary:hover{ background:#f0b25c; color:#10171a;}
  button.act.done-btn{ border-color:var(--teal); color:var(--teal); }

  .reveal{ margin-top:16px; border-top:1px dashed var(--line); padding-top:16px; display:none; }
  .reveal.show{ display:block; }
  .reveal .who{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10.5px; color:var(--amber); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.1em; margin-bottom:10px;}
  .reveal-body{ font-size:13.5px; line-height:1.75; color:var(--text); }
  .reveal-body p{ margin:0 0 10px;}
  .reveal-body ul, .reveal-body ol{ margin:0 0 10px; padding-left:20px; }
  .reveal-body li{ margin-bottom:5px; }
  .reveal-body .code{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:12.5px; background:var(--bg); border:1px solid var(--line); border-radius:3px; padding:12px 14px; display:block; white-space:pre-wrap; color:var(--text-dim); margin:8px 0;}
  .reveal-body .code .kw{ color:var(--teal); }
  .reveal-body .code .flag{ color:var(--amber); }
  .reveal-body table{ width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:12.5px; margin:8px 0 12px;}
  .reveal-body th, .reveal-body td{ border:1px solid var(--line); padding:7px 9px; text-align:left;}
  .reveal-body th{ font-family:var(--mono); font-size:10.5px; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--text-dim); letter-spacing:.05em;}

  .status-stamp{
    display:inline-flex; align-items:center; gap:6px; font-family:var(--mono); font-size:11px;
    color:var(--teal); border:1px solid var(--teal); padding:4px 10px; border-radius:3px; margin-bottom:18px;
  }
  .nav-foot{ display:flex; justify-content:space-between; margin-top:36px; padding-top:20px; border-top:1px solid var(--line); }

  ::-webkit-scrollbar{ width:8px; }
  ::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb{ background:var(--line); border-radius:4px; }

  @media (max-width: 760px){
    .app{ flex-direction:column; }
    .rail{ width:100%; max-height:60vh; }
    .main{ padding:24px 20px 60px; }
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="app">
  <div class="rail">
    <div class="rail-head">
      <div class="kicker">Field Training — Full Cycle</div>
      <h1>Day One: LIMS BA</h1>
      <p>Case file: <b style="color:var(--amber)">Damaged Sample Intake Alert</b> — Dublin / Madrid / Lisbon. Every activity a BA runs on this project, start to finish.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rail-scroll" id="stageList"></div>
    <div class="rail-foot">
      <div class="progress-track"><div class="progress-fill" id="progressFill"></div></div>
      <div class="progress-text" id="progressText">0 / 0 stages complete</div>
      <button class="reset-btn" id="resetBtn">RESET TRAINING PROGRESS</button>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="main" id="main"></div>
</div>

<script>
/* ================= DATA ================= */
const STAGES = [

/* ---------- CATEGORY A: INTAKE & DISCOVERY ---------- */
{ cat:"A . Intake & Discovery", id:"intake", label:"Ticket Intake & Triage", tag:"Day 1 - 08:45",
  title:"The Ticket Lands", sub:"Before you talk to anyone, learn to read a request the way a BA reads it - as a gap, not a task.",
  mentor:[
   "A ticket dropped overnight: <span class='term'>\"Damaged samples not being flagged consistently.\"</span> Forwarded by the PM with one line: \"scope this for next sprint?\" Nobody wrote you a spec - a vague ticket is an invitation to go find out what's happening, not a to-do item.",
   "Before I let you near a stakeholder, give me your discovery prep: questions about the business gap, not the software."
  ],
  task:"Write 5 questions you'd want answered before your first discovery call with the Madrid QC lead. Don't ask about screens yet.",
  placeholder:"1. Who first noticed this and how often does it happen?\n2. ...",
  reveal:"<ol><li><b>Who reported it, and who else is affected?</b> Scope tells you if it's local or systemic.</li><li><b>What's the current workaround?</b> The real process, not the documented one.</li><li><b>How often, and what's the cost of getting it wrong?</b> Frequency times severity decides urgency.</li><li><b>What systems does this touch today?</b> Accessioning only, or does it cascade into workflow and reporting?</li><li><b>Is there a regulatory angle?</b> Sample condition brushes up against ISO 15189 and ALCOA+ data integrity.</li></ol><p><b>Why this matters:</b> none of these are \"what button do we add.\" You gather the shape of the problem before you solution it.</p>"
},
{ cat:"A . Intake & Discovery", id:"discovery", label:"Stakeholder Interview & As-Is Mapping", tag:"Day 1 - 10:00",
  title:"Shadowing, Then the Madrid Call", sub:"You watch the real process before you write anything. Then you turn messy field notes into a usable document.",
  mentor:[
   "Twenty minutes shadowing the Dublin accessioning bench before any call. A tech logs a sample with a crushed box lid, writes a sticky note, moves on - the sticky note is the whole problem: it lives outside the system, no audit trail.",
   "Here are the raw notes from the shadow session plus the Madrid call. Turn this into a clean 5-6 step As-Is."
  ],
  task:"Raw notes: damaged samples happen 2-3x per week per site. tech writes sticky note, sample still gets 'received' status either way. no 'damaged' flag exists. Madrid confirms same workaround - sometimes note gets lost, sample goes to testing, result comes back weird, THEN someone realizes it was damaged. no audit trail. Lisbon not contacted yet.\n\nWrite a clean As-Is.",
  placeholder:"Step 1: Sample arrives at accessioning bench...",
  reveal:"<ol><li>Sample arrives and is visually inspected by the technician.</li><li>Regardless of damage, technician logs status <b>Received</b> - no distinct damaged state exists.</li><li>If damage is visible, a physical sticky note is written, outside the system.</li><li>Sample proceeds toward testing in parallel with the workaround - no system control stops it.</li><li><b>Failure path (confirmed):</b> the note is lost, the sample is tested, an unexpected result surfaces days later and gets retroactively traced to the damage.</li><li>No audit trail exists for the damage observation or the eventual discovery - gap confirmed in Dublin and Madrid; Lisbon unconfirmed.</li></ol><p><b>What a strong As-Is does:</b> it names the failure path, not just the happy path - because that's exactly what your requirement has to close.</p>"
},
{ cat:"A . Intake & Discovery", id:"brd", label:"Writing the BRD", tag:"Day 1 - 16:00",
  title:"Putting a Frame Around the Problem", sub:"Before code exists, this is the document stakeholders sign off on - and the one that saves you when scope creep shows up later.",
  mentor:[
   "Story-level requirements are for developers. Before that, you write a short <span class='term'>BRD</span> - Business Requirements Document - that a PM and stakeholders agree to: purpose, what's in, what's explicitly out, who's affected, how you'll know it worked.",
   "Use everything from the last two stages. The \"out of scope\" line matters as much as the \"in scope\" one - it's what you point to later instead of relying on memory."
  ],
  task:"Write a compact BRD: Purpose / In-scope / Out-of-scope / Stakeholders / Success criteria, for the damaged sample alert.",
  placeholder:"Purpose:\nIn scope:\nOut of scope:\nStakeholders:\nSuccess criteria:",
  reveal:"<p><b>Purpose:</b> Replace the manual sticky-note workaround with a system-enforced damaged-sample flag, block, and audit trail.</p><p><b>In scope:</b> Accessioning intake flag, automatic block from testing, audit log entry, QC notification - Dublin, Madrid, Lisbon.</p><p><b>Out of scope:</b> Retroactive re-testing of historical samples; client-facing report template changes; instrument-level automatic damage detection (visual inspection stays manual).</p><p><b>Stakeholders:</b> Madrid QC lead (requester), Dublin & Lisbon QC leads, accessioning technicians (3 sites), IT support (notification monitoring), Product Manager.</p><p><b>Success criteria:</b> Zero damaged samples reach testing without an exception flag, for 30 consecutive days post-hypercare.</p><p><b>Why \"out of scope\" earns its place:</b> when someone later asks for instrument-level auto-detection, you point to this document instead of relitigating scope from memory.</p>"
},
{ cat:"A . Intake & Discovery", id:"raid", label:"Starting the RAID Log", tag:"Day 2 - 09:00",
  title:"Risks, Assumptions, Issues, Dependencies", sub:"A living register, not a one-off note - this is what separates 'I think I mentioned that' from a defensible record.",
  mentor:[
   "Before this goes further, start the formal RAID log. Four buckets people constantly mix up: an <span class='term'>Assumption</span> is believed true but unconfirmed. A <span class='term'>Risk</span> is something that could go wrong. An <span class='term'>Issue</span> is already happening and blocking you now. A <span class='term'>Dependency</span> is something you rely on another team or system for.",
   "Classify these four raw items correctly."
  ],
  task:"Classify each as Risk / Assumption / Issue / Dependency:\n1) Reason codes might not match across Lisbon (unconfirmed)\n2) Notification service historically flaky in Madrid\n3) Waiting on Lisbon QC lead's confirmation email\n4) Feature depends on the notification microservice team's retry logic shipping first",
  placeholder:"1: ...\n2: ...\n3: ...\n4: ...",
  reveal:"<table><tr><th>Item</th><th>Category</th><th>Why</th></tr><tr><td>Reason codes may not match in Lisbon</td><td><b>Assumption</b></td><td>Believed true, not yet confirmed</td></tr><tr><td>Notification service flaky in Madrid</td><td><b>Risk</b></td><td>Could cause missed alerts - hasn't happened on this feature yet</td></tr><tr><td>Waiting on Lisbon's confirmation</td><td><b>Issue</b> (borderline)</td><td>Already actively blocking you today</td></tr><tr><td>Depends on notification team's retry logic</td><td><b>Dependency</b></td><td>Another team's deliverable you rely on</td></tr></table><p>This log isn't paperwork - it's the thing you point to in Stage C4 when one of these actually materializes.</p>"
},

/* ---------- CATEGORY B: DEFINE THE BACKLOG ---------- */
{ cat:"B . Define the Backlog", id:"epic", label:"Creating the Epic (Azure DevOps)", tag:"Day 2 - 11:00",
  title:"Opening Azure DevOps for Real", sub:"Everything downstream hangs off this. Title and description need to survive someone reading it with zero context, six months from now.",
  mentor:[
   "Time to actually create the work item. Everything - Features, Stories - links up to this Epic. Write it so a stranger reading it cold understands the 'why', not just the 'what.'"
  ],
  task:"Write Epic fields: Title / Description / Business value statement / initial linked Features (names only).",
  placeholder:"Title:\nDescription:\nBusiness value:\nFeatures:",
  reveal:"<div class='code'><span class='kw'>Title:</span> Sample Exception Handling - Damaged Sample Intake\n<span class='kw'>Description:</span> Enable LIMS to formally capture, block, and audit damaged samples at accessioning across Dublin, Madrid, and Lisbon, replacing the current manual sticky-note workaround.\n<span class='kw'>Business value:</span> Eliminates undetected testing of damaged samples (data integrity / regulatory risk) and closes an audit trail gap flagged by Madrid QC.\n<span class='kw'>Linked Features:</span> Accessioning Exception Flagging . Exception Notification & Escalation . Exception Audit Trail</div><p><b>Why it matters:</b> an Epic without a business value line is just a folder. That line is what a PM later lifts straight into a steering committee deck (Stage F5) - write it for that reuse.</p>"
},
{ cat:"B . Define the Backlog", id:"features", label:"Epic to Feature to Story Breakdown", tag:"Day 2 - 11:30",
  title:"Splitting the Epic Into Buildable Pieces", sub:"Feature = a deliverable slice within the Program Increment. Story = something a team can actually finish in one sprint.",
  mentor:[
   "Take the \"Accessioning Exception Flagging\" Feature and break it into 2-3 Stories. Rule of thumb: if a Story can't reasonably finish in one sprint, it's actually a Feature wearing a disguise."
  ],
  task:"Break Feature 'Accessioning Exception Flagging' into 2-3 sprint-sized Stories.",
  placeholder:"Story 1: ...\nStory 2: ...\nStory 3: ...",
  reveal:"<div class='code'><span class='kw'>Feature:</span> Accessioning Exception Flagging\n<span class='kw'>Story 1:</span> Add \"Damaged\" intake condition option at accessioning\n<span class='kw'>Story 2:</span> Enforce system block from testing queue when status = Exception-Damaged\n<span class='kw'>Story 3:</span> Persist reason code(s) on the exception record</div><p>Each one is independently testable and shippable - none depends on finishing the others first to demonstrate value, which is what makes them real Stories rather than a Feature split arbitrarily in three.</p>"
},
{ cat:"B . Define the Backlog", id:"story", label:"Writing the Story + Gherkin AC", tag:"Day 2 - 14:00",
  title:"The Artifact Engineers Actually Build From", sub:"It has to survive contact with a developer who wasn't in the room for discovery.",
  mentor:[
   "Take Story 1 and 2 together and write one combined story with Gherkin acceptance criteria - Given/When/Then, unambiguous enough that a developer and a tester read it the same way.",
   "Build in the audit trail requirement explicitly. In a regulated lab, if it isn't logged with who/when/what-changed, it didn't happen."
  ],
  task:"Write the user story (As a / I want / So that) plus Gherkin AC for: flag a sample damaged at accessioning, block it from testing, log it.",
  placeholder:"As a Lab Accessioning Technician\nI want to...\nSo that...\n\nScenario: ...",
  reveal:"<div class='code'><span class='kw'>Story:</span>\nAs a Lab Accessioning Technician\nI want to flag a sample as \"Exception - Damaged\" at intake\nSo that damaged samples are quarantined and cannot reach testing until reviewed\n\n<span class='kw'>Scenario:</span> Sample flagged as damaged at accessioning\n<span class='kw'>Given</span> a sample is being registered at accessioning\n<span class='kw'>And</span> the technician selects \"Damaged\" as the intake condition\n<span class='kw'>When</span> the sample record is saved\n<span class='kw'>Then</span> the system sets status to <span class='flag'>Exception - Damaged</span>\n<span class='kw'>And</span> the sample is blocked from the testing queue\n<span class='kw'>And</span> an audit entry is created with user, timestamp, and reason code\n<span class='kw'>And</span> the QC lead for the originating lab is notified</div><p>No UI description anywhere in here - you specified behavior, not layout, so it survives a redesign.</p>"
},
{ cat:"B . Define the Backlog", id:"estimation", label:"Estimation / Planning Poker", tag:"Day 2 - 15:30",
  title:"Sizing the Work as a Team", sub:"The goal isn't consensus math - it's surfacing the hidden knowledge behind an outlier vote.",
  mentor:[
   "Team estimates in Fibonacci-ish points (1,2,3,5,8,13), voting simultaneously so nobody anchors on the first number said out loud.",
   "Three stories just got voted. Decide the final estimate for each, and flag which one actually needs a discussion round."
  ],
  task:"Story 1 votes: 2,3,3,2,5. Story 2 votes: 8,5,13,8,8. Story 3 votes: 1,1,2,1,1. Give final estimates and note which needs discussion.",
  placeholder:"Story 1: ...\nStory 2: ...\nStory 3: ...",
  reveal:"<p><b>Story 1 to 3.</b> The lone 5 is a mild outlier; quick discussion, group converges down.</p><p><b>Story 2 - needs real discussion, don't average it.</b> Spread of 5 to 13 is wide - the 13-voter is seeing hidden complexity (very likely the notification-team dependency from the RAID log). Ask them to explain <i>first</i>, before anyone else re-votes.</p><p><b>Story 3 to 1.</b> Tight spread, converges instantly, move on.</p><p>The point of poker: a wide spread is information, not noise to be smoothed over.</p>"
},
{ cat:"B . Define the Backlog", id:"grooming", label:"Backlog Grooming & WSJF", tag:"Day 3 - 09:00",
  title:"Where Does This Sit in the Queue?", sub:"A good story means nothing if it never gets prioritized. This is how a BA earns trust with a Product Manager.",
  mentor:[
   "Prioritize with a simplified <span class='term'>WSJF</span> (SAFe): (Business Value + Time Criticality + Risk Reduction) / Job Size. Higher score wins.",
   "Rank these four, and be ready to defend the ranking out loud - whoever explains the number wins the argument, not whoever talks loudest."
  ],
  task:"Rank using (BV+TC+RR)/Size:\nA. Damaged-sample auto-flag - BV8 TC5 RR3 Size5\nB. Barcode label reprint button - BV3 TC2 RR1 Size2\nC. Multi-level result approval workflow - BV9 TC4 RR6 Size8\nD. Client report PDF branding update - BV4 TC1 RR1 Size3",
  placeholder:"A: (8+5+3)/5 = ...\nFinal rank: ...",
  reveal:"<table><tr><th>Item</th><th>Calc</th><th>Score</th></tr><tr><td>A</td><td>(8+5+3)/5</td><td><b>3.20</b></td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>(3+2+1)/2</td><td><b>3.00</b></td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>(9+4+6)/8</td><td><b>2.38</b></td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>(4+1+1)/3</td><td><b>2.00</b></td></tr></table><p><b>Rank: A to B to C to D.</b> The interesting defense is A vs C: C has the highest raw value (9), but WSJF punishes the big job size on purpose - ship the smaller win now, get to C next.</p>"
},

/* ---------- CATEGORY C: SAFe EVENTS & CEREMONIES ---------- */
{ cat:"C . SAFe Events & Ceremonies", id:"sprintplan", label:"Sprint Planning", tag:"Day 3 - 10:00",
  title:"Committing to What Actually Fits", sub:"Priority order isn't the same as what fits. This is where velocity, buffer, and sprint goal come together.",
  mentor:[
   "Team velocity: 20 points per sprint. Never plan to 100% - leave headroom for unplanned interrupts (production support, edge cases like Stage D1)."
  ],
  task:"WSJF-ranked stories: 5, 8, 3, 8, 5 points. Velocity 20. Decide what's committed this sprint and write the sprint goal.",
  placeholder:"Committed: ...\nSprint Goal: ...",
  reveal:"<p><b>Committed:</b> 5 + 8 + 3 = 16 points. The next 8-point story would push to 24 - over capacity with zero buffer, so it rolls to next sprint rather than being squeezed in.</p><p><b>Sprint Goal:</b> \"By end of sprint, accessioning technicians in all three labs can flag a sample as damaged and have it automatically blocked from testing.\"</p><p>Leaving 4 points of headroom isn't slack - it's insurance against the interrupt that always shows up mid-sprint.</p>"
},
{ cat:"C . SAFe Events & Ceremonies", id:"piplanning", label:"PI Planning", tag:"Program Increment - Day 1-2",
  title:"The Whole Train, One Room, Two Days", sub:"SAFe's quarterly event: every team on the Agile Release Train plans the next 10-12 weeks together, out loud, with dependencies and risks on the table.",
  mentor:[
   "Vision and context come from leadership; teams draft their own plan; cross-team dependencies get mapped on a shared program board; risks get sorted with <span class='term'>ROAM</span> - Resolved, Owned, Accepted, Mitigated; and the event closes with a <span class='term'>confidence vote</span>, teams fist-voting 1-5 on their own plan. Anything under 3 gets addressed on the spot, not quietly waved through.",
   "Draft your team's contribution."
  ],
  task:"Write 2 PI Objectives (with a business value 1-10 each), one cross-team dependency, and classify one risk using ROAM.",
  placeholder:"Objective 1: ...\nObjective 2: ...\nDependency: ...\nRisk (ROAM): ...",
